<seg id="1">Report on the results of parallel control of value added tax administration between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic carried out in 2005</seg>
<seg id="2">Úvodní slovo</seg>
<seg id="3">The submitted material informs about the course and results of parallel inspections carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, which focused on the management of value added tax and the use of the VIES information system (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System – System for the exchange of value added tax).</seg>
<seg id="4">In May 2004 the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic entered the European Union, so the income from value added tax affect not only the state budgets of both countries, but also the budget of the European Union as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="5">Parallel control actions were focused mainly on checking the procedure of tax administrators in verifying the amount of value added tax carried out during business transactions carried out between the individual Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="6">The introduction of the VIES system enabled electronic exchange of information on the registration of the value added tax payers in individual Member States of the European Union and commercial transactions carried out by these payers.</seg>
<seg id="7">The discrepancy between the data in the VIES system and the tax return data for the value added taxpayer should notify the tax administrator on suspicious cases and allow the discovery of tax evasion or fraud.</seg>
<seg id="8">The benefit carried out by parallel audits consisted not only of exchange of information on financial or tax authorities in the administration of value added tax, but especially in verification of the use of the VIES system during the inspection of the claim for exemption from value added tax during intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="9">The knowledge gained in the implementation of parallel inspections is beneficial for the development of mutual cooperation and will be used in the implementation of other parallel inspections in cooperation with the audit institutions of the European Union Member States.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the results of parallel control of value added tax administration for the period from 1. 5. 2004 until 30. 6. 2005</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Control number: (CZ) 05/19 (SK) 22/2005</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of Control: (CZ) Taxation of Value Added Tax, (SK) Checking the procedure of tax authorities in administration, control and tax collection of value added and fulfilling tasks within the VIES system to exchange information between EU Member States</seg>
<seg id="14">The Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the “NKÚ, Czech Republic”) and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the “NSAO”) concluded on 12 December. 9. 2005 Contract on cooperation in control activities.</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the contract was the cooperation in the carried out parallel auditing events “The Administration of Value Added Tax”, included in the Audit Plan of the SAO, the Czech Republic for 2005 under No. 05/19 and “Checking the Procedure of Tax Authorities at the Contract, Control and Enforcement of the Value and Fence of Tasks within the VIES System on the Mission of Informáci informs the Department of Member States of the EC”, included in the Audit Plan of the SAO under No. 22/2005.</seg>
<seg id="16">Parallelly carried out control actions had the character of coordinated control.</seg>
<seg id="17">The result of the joint coordinated control was processed within the meaning of the European Exercise Regulation No. 31 for the INTOSAI control standards.</seg>
<seg id="18">The cooperation consisted in the exchange of information in the extent specified by the concluded contract and in the elaboration of the joint final report on the outcome of parallel inspections.</seg>
<seg id="19">The purpose of the coordinated audit was to verify selected cases of delivery and purchase of goods at suspicious commercial transactions between tax payers from the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the “ČR”) and the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as “SR”).</seg>
<seg id="20">Both parties are contractually committed to providing information from public sources, from the VIES electronic system (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System) and data on received and sent requests to verify business transactions between the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="21">The audits were carried out in parallel from June to December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="22">On the territory of the Czech Republic, the inspection was carried out by the state budget department and territorial trade unions of Central Bohemia, northwest Bohemia, South Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and North Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited bodies were the Ministry of Finance and 12 Financial Offices: Financial Office in Mladá Boleslav, Financial Office in Cologne, Financial Office in Teplice, Financial Office in Karlovy Vary, Financial Office in Tábor, Financial Office Brno III, Financial Office in Znojmo, Financial Office in Zlín, Financial Office in Šumperk, Financial Office Ostrava I, Financial Office for Prague 7 and Financial Office for Prague 9.</seg>
<seg id="24">The auditing operation on the territory of the Slovak Republic was carried out by the Financial and Tax Section of the SAO in cooperation with Expozitrami NKÚ SR Banská Bystrica and Košice at 9 selected tax offices: Tax head Bratislava I, Tax Úrad Komárno, Tax Trade Trenčín, Tax Office Prievidza, Tax Office Zvolen, Tax Office Dolný Kubín, Tax Office Košice II, Tax Office Košice V and Tax Office Michalovce.</seg>
<seg id="25">Target of controls:</seg>
<seg id="26">The aim of the parallel auditing events was to examine the procedure of financial or tax authorities in the administration of value added tax (hereinafter referred to as “VAT”) after the inclusion of the Czech Republic and Slovakia into the single internal market of the European Union (hereinafter referred to as the “EU”) and to examine the use of the VIES electronic information system, especially when controlling the claim for exemption from VAT.</seg>
<seg id="27">The audited period of the coordinated control was from 1. 5. 2004 until 30. 6. 2005.</seg>
<seg id="28">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions In EU Member States, an electronic system VIES is introduced, which allows tax administrators to check whether the supplier was entitled to free taxable performance from VAT, and in the country of destination it allows to verify whether the acquired goods acquired properly confessed and taxed.</seg>
<seg id="29">The VIES system is not centralized within the EU, each Member State develops its own system.</seg>
<seg id="30">The audit was found differences of national systems of VIES in the Czech Republic and Slovakia in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="31">In summary reports, the delivery values of goods to other EU Member States are stated, the values of the services provided are not stated in the aggregate reports.</seg>
<seg id="32">Data from aggregate reports submitted by Czech payers are processed in the Czech Republic at the level of financial authorities, where they are compared with data on delivery of goods to other EU Member States listed in VAT tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="33">Financial authorities transmit data from aggregate reports to the Ministry of Finance (CLO), which is sent to other EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="34">In Slovakia, data from aggregate reports submitted by Slovak tax authorities are only transferred to electronic form and processed centrally on the Slovak Tax Directorate (CLO).</seg>
<seg id="35">In the Czech Republic, the payers show the value of delivery of goods and the value of the provision of services to other EU Member States on separate lines of tax returns, which allows to compare the values referred to in aggregate reports with the values of delivery of goods according to tax returns and identify their possible differences.</seg>
<seg id="36">In Slovakia, the values of the delivered goods and services provided to other EU Member States are reported collectively on the common line of tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="37">As a result, the system does not allow the system to automatically identify the differences between the values of the delivery of goods according to tax returns and aggregate reports.</seg>
<seg id="38">Separate reporting of the values of delivery of goods in VAT tax returns allows you to use the results of the comparison of data when checking the exemption of deliveries to the EU from VAT.</seg>
<seg id="39">The specified data from the aggregate reports submitted to the payers in other EU Member States are processed on CLO and compared to the value of the purchase of goods stated by the payer from the Czech Republic or Slovakia in tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="40">In Slovakia, these data are sent to the tax authorities and the tax administrators themselves decide which cases will verify the differences.</seg>
<seg id="41">In the Czech Republic, the Ministry of Finance (CLO), which quantified the differences between delivery values and the purchase of goods, shall be determined by the tax administrator, and the relevant tax authorities shall give a list of these cases.</seg>
<seg id="42">This ensures that the most important deviations will be verified whether VAT was awarded in the correct amount when purchasing goods.</seg>
<seg id="43">The auditing operation also pointed out some problems in the VAT administration system complications caused by different reporting of intra-community transactions (i.e. delivery and purchase of goods made by payers from different EU Member States):</seg>
<seg id="44">The summary reports are served in the EU for each calendar quarter and the maximum period for processing and sending data to other EU Member States is set for 3 months from the end of the relevant quarter.</seg>
<seg id="45">The shortening of the period for which the aggregate reports are administered, one month, together with the shortening of the deadline for their processing, would allow earlier access to the data in the VIES system.</seg>
<seg id="46">The tax administrators could thus effectively examine whether VAT was awarded in the correct amount during intra-Community purchases.</seg>
<seg id="47">At the same time, the administration of tax returns and aggregate reports for the same taxation period (month) would allow faster verification whether the payer reported on the total report and tax return of the same value of delivery of goods to the EU.</seg>
<seg id="48">The differences between the values of the delivery of goods reported by payers from the EU and the values of the acquisition of goods reported by payers from the Czech Republic, or Slovakia were caused by a different reporting of data on intra-Community delivery and acquisition in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="49">These include, for example, the introduction of received advances in aggregate reports, or reporting intra-Community deliveries in a summary report of the supplier in a different quarter than intra-Community acquisition in the VAT tax return of the supplier.</seg>
<seg id="50">The unification of the conditions for reporting this data within the EU would lead to streamlining the control activities of the tax administrators of individual Member States.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR was also focused on verifying selected intra-community transactions carried out between the two states.</seg>
<seg id="52">Together, a total of 40 cases of commercial transactions carried out between 29 Czech and 32 Slovak tax entities were examined, where there were doubts about their implementation, virtually suspicion of tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="53">The SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO, found the following facts:</seg>
<seg id="54">tax entities reported in their tax returns for the purpose of unauthorized acquisition of an excessive VAT deduction realization of intra-Community transactions, whose implementation did not actually occur;</seg>
<seg id="55">tax entities showed intra-Community delivery within the carousel shops, in which several times the value of deliveries in the purpose of drawing excessive VAT deductions occurred;</seg>
<seg id="56">Suppliers reported VAT and aggregate reports of intra-Community delivery of goods exempt from VAT to buyers who were so-called “lost companies” and tax on acquired goods did not admit;</seg>
<seg id="57">suppliers carried out intra-Community delivery of goods exempt from VAT for tax entities that were not registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="58">In these cases, the delivery of VAT should not be exempt and should be subject to tax in the supplier's country;</seg>
<seg id="59">Suppliers reported intra-Community delivery in a higher value in their tax returns than in which they reported intra-communary acquisition makers, and in some cases VAT was awarded in the wrong amount.</seg>
<seg id="60">From the knowledge obtained in the control event, the VIES system provides tax administrators with information necessary to check the correct application of VAT during intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="61">The tax administrators should pay increased attention especially to the consistent verification of the differences between the data reported by VAT payers and the VIES system and the use of all information in tax proceedings.</seg>
