<seg id="371">By verifying selected transactions, the tax administration of both countries has been found to have detected the tax administration of both countries in cases of companies that have implemented fictitious intra-Community business transactions in order to obtain excessive VAT deductions as well as cases where the receipts have not entered VAT from the received deliveries of goods in the right amount.</seg>
<seg id="372">The audits were further found in the processing and use of data from the VIES tax administrators of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="373">The audit also pointed out problems caused by different reporting of intra-community delivery data and purchases of goods in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="374">The unification of the conditions for reporting this data within the EU would lead to streamlining the control activities of the tax administrators of individual Member States.</seg>
<seg id="375">By verifying the procedure of financial or tax authorities in the administration of VAT and the use of the VIES system, the financial or tax authorities did not use all the possibilities of the VIES system and the relevant legal permissions.</seg>
<seg id="376">It was also found that the VIES system did not provide up-to-date information on the supply of goods and validity of tax entities for VAT in all cases.</seg>
<seg id="377">The SAO of SR compared data on the occurrence of incorrect data in SH, processed before the start of the audit, with data processed after the end of the audit performance.</seg>
<seg id="378">Compared to this data, it was clear that the SAO's audit had an influence not only on reducing the number of SH with incorrect VAT number, but also to reducing the number of corrected errors in SH.</seg>
<seg id="379">In the case of inconsistencies in the reported data of the SAO, tax authorities requested the implementation of local investigations, or to carry out tax inspections.</seg>
<seg id="380">The SAO, the Czech Republic, did not have such an opportunity within the framework of applicable legislation in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="381">The knowledge obtained from the auditing actions resulted that the VIES system provided the tax administrators with basic information necessary to check the correct application of VAT during intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="382">Since there is still a space for tax evasion in this area, it is necessary to pay increased attention when managing VAT.</seg>
<seg id="383">Communications</seg>
<seg id="384">This report was prepared in Czech, English and Slovak and signed by the President of the Supreme Audit Office, Czech Republic and Chairman of Naj Increšie's Audit Office of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
</p>
