<p>
<seg id="1">Parallel control of value added tax administration and excise duty between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Úvodní slovo</seg>
<seg id="3">This information material gives an overview of the course and results of parallel control actions carried out by the Supreme Audit Office and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, which focused on the administration of the value added and excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="4">Cooperation between the highest audit authorities of both countries was carried out on the basis of a contract on cooperation in the auditing operation concluded in February 2004.</seg>
<seg id="5">The topic of parallel control actions was selected with regard to the fact that indirect taxes significantly participate in the income of state budgets of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="6">The value of value added tax, enabling the refund of excessive deduction, provides space for tax fraud or leaks.</seg>
<seg id="7">High consumption tax rates, especially tobacco and tobacco products, alcohol and mineral oils, mean high profit for those who escape the taxation of illegal sales of this goods.</seg>
<seg id="8">Tax fraud are a problem not only in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, but also in other countries of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="9">Due to the need to address this issue comprehensively throughout the European Union, a working group of VAT Working Group was created by the highest audit institutions of the European Union member states, into which the highest control authorities of both countries are actively involved.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefit of the auditing events carried out can be seen not only in the exchange of experience, but especially in common efforts to identify the problem areas of indirect taxes in order to limit the space for tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="11">The acquired experience and knowledge will be used within the planned inspections of indirect taxes focused primarily on the involvement of tax administrators of both countries to the VIES system, enabling to control the movement of goods between the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="12">Report on the results of value of value added tax administration and consumer tax for the period 2002 and 2003</seg>
<seg id="13">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="14">Control number: (CZ) 04/07 (SK) 18/2004</seg>
<seg id="15">Subject of control:</seg>
<seg id="16">(CZ) Value Added Tax and excise duty</seg>
<seg id="17">(SK) Checking the procedure of the tax administrator in administration, control and tax collection of value added and consumables</seg>
<seg id="18">11.2. 2004 the Treaty on Cooperation in the Audit Office between the Supreme Audit Office (hereinafter referred to as the “NKÚ”) and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the “N of the SAO”) was concluded. The subject of the contract was cooperation in the carried out parallel auditing events “ Value Added Tax and Consumption Tax”, included in the Audit Plan of the SAO for 2004 under No 04/07 and “Checking the procedure of the Administrator shall be given in the procedure, control and enforcement of the value and payment taxes", included in the Audit Plan of the SAO under No. 18/2004.</seg>
<seg id="19">The cooperation consisted in the exchange of information in the extent specified by the concluded contract and in the elaboration of the joint final report on the result of the audits.</seg>
<seg id="20">Both parties undertook to provide each other with information from public sources, from the database of customs administration and from the writings of tax entities maintained by the financial authorities in the Czech Republic and tax authorities in the Slovak Republic, which the contracting parties could not obtain in the control of the application of value added tax and excise duty in import and exports from sources in the territory of the respective state.</seg>
<seg id="21">The audits were carried out in parallel from January to August 2004.</seg>
<seg id="22">On the territory of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "ČR") the inspection was carried out by the state budget department and territorial departments of South Bohemia, northeast Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and North Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited bodies were the Directorate-General of customs duties and 12 selected financial offices: Financial Office for Prague 1, Financial Office for Prague 3, Financial Office in České Budějovice, Financial Office in Frýdek-Místek, Financial Office in Hodonín, Financial Office in Jihlava, Financial Office in Kostelec nad Orlicí, Financial Office in Kroměříž, Financial Office in Písek, Financial Office in Rožnov pod Radhoštěm, Financial Office in Ústí nad Orlicí, Financial Office in Velké Meziříčí.</seg>
<seg id="24">The audit on the territory of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the “SR”) was carried out by the Section of Tax and Customs Administration of the SAO in cooperation with Expozitrami NKÚ SR Banská Bystrica and Košice on 10 selected tax authorities:</seg>
<seg id="25">Tax head Bratislava pre-selected tax entities, Tax head Bratislava III, Tax destination Trnava, Tax head Pú-chov, Tax counsel Banská Bystrica I, Tax council Liptovský Mikuláš, Tax council Žilina I, Tax fate Žilina II, Tax head Košice I and Tax head Košice IV.</seg>
<seg id="26">Goal of control</seg>
<seg id="27">The aim of the auditing operation was to examine the fulfilment of the obligations of financial or tax authorities and customs authorities in the administration of value added tax and consumer taxes focusing on the selection of these taxes in import and export of goods and services.</seg>
<seg id="28">The aim of the international cooperation was to verify imports and exports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and Slovakia in the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of Slovakia and their subsequent verification in tax returns on the relevant financial or tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited period was 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="30">2. Recapitulation of control results</seg>
<seg id="31">2.1. General evaluation of control activities</seg>
<seg id="32">Within the framework of the International Cooperation of the SAO, the SAO handed over from the customs database of the Czech Republic 22 206 items of uniform customs declarations (hereinafter referred to as “JCD") on imports and exports of goods between the Czech Republic and Slovakia and the SAO handed over the SAO from the customs database of SR 30 221 items JCD.</seg>
<seg id="33">Comparison of the specified items JCD from the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of the Slovak Republic was carried out.</seg>
<seg id="34">A total of 43% of the related items of JCD were assigned to the 5 883 selected items of JCD from the customs database of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="35">A total of 26% of the related items JCD were assigned to the 12 343 selected items of JCD from the Slovakia's customs database.</seg>
<seg id="36">Based on the unaccepted items of JCD, a selection of writings of tax entities was carried out on financial or tax offices, where the reported imports and exports were further verified in cooperation with the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="37">Based on the exchange of information from the documents of the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and Slovakia and financial, or tax authorities, the implementation of reported imports and exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia was verified in the second state.</seg>
<seg id="38">The SAO and the SAO of Slovakia carried out a joint pilot control on the border customs crossing Starý Hrozenkov - Drietoma, during which both stakeholders worked closely in verifying the correctness of the data on the movement of goods between the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="39">The audit has not found shortcomings in the registration of selected cases of imports and exports of goods implemented in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="40">International cooperation enabled the verification of commercial transactions carried out between business partners from both countries and pointed out deficiencies in the records of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="41">2.2. Summary of control results</seg>
<seg id="42">In the field of international cooperation, the SAO and the SAO of Slovakia focused on imports and exports of alcohol and spirits, tobacco and tobacco products, computers and computer components, mobile phones and their components, or other types of goods.</seg>
<seg id="43">Based on the inspection of the writings of tax entities on selected financial, or tax offices of the SAO, he asked for verifying the realization of exports of goods reported to 40 JCD in the total statistical value of 15 301 093 CZK and the SAO of the Slovak Republic verification of exports in the statistical value of 56 989 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="44">The SAO and the SAO of SR found out, among other things, the following facts:</seg>
<seg id="45">- business transactions were not declared the same way on both sides, which was difficult to identify the corresponding imports and exports in the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of Slovakia,</seg>
<seg id="46">- error in entering data into customs databases has prevented identifying some imports or exports,</seg>
<seg id="47">- some exports from the Czech Republic were not proven adequate imports to Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="48">In these cases, there is a reasonable suspicion of fictitious exports of goods for unauthorized application of value added tax deductions,</seg>
<seg id="49">- tax entities did not meet some statutory obligations in reporting imports and exports in tax returns to tax added tax,</seg>
<seg id="50">- in the activities of financial or tax authorities in the administration of value added tax and consumer taxes and in their cooperation with customs authorities, deficiencies were found.</seg>
<seg id="51">In the area of value added tax and excise duty, it will continue to be paid attention to international trade in order to effectively minimize tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="52">It is important especially to improve the quality of tax administrators in the performance of value added tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="53">The basis of effective control of excise duty is the control of circulation of documents, systematic physical control of goods and mutual exchange of information during import and export of goods.</seg>
<seg id="54">3. Description of the state in the area of value added tax and excise duty</seg>
<seg id="55">Value Added Tax</seg>
<seg id="56">Value added tax (hereinafter referred to as the “VAT") was selected by financial or tax authorities from taxable fulfilment carried out in the Czech Republic and customs authorities when importing goods.</seg>
<seg id="57">The tax revenues were given by the difference between the selected own tax obligations and returned excessive VAT deductions.</seg>
<seg id="58">VAT revenues at customs authorities were given to the amount of selected taxes.</seg>
<seg id="59">The tax selected customs authorities in accordance with the basic principles of the VAT mechanism reflected in the tax deductions applied to financial or tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="60">Most financial or tax authorities exceeded excessive VAT deductions over tax obligations.</seg>
<seg id="61">VAT is one of the key taxes in terms of state budget income, as roughly 31% participated in tax revenues of the state budget of the Czech Republic and approximately 42% on tax revenues of the state budget of Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="62">The total VAT collection in the Czech Republic reached 162.9 billion in 2003. CZK.</seg>
<seg id="63">The financial and customs authorities have selected CZK 394.3 billion in 2003 for VAT. CZK and returned excessive VAT deductions amounted to 231,4 billion. CZK.</seg>
<seg id="64">The total VAT collection in Slovakia reached CZK 83.8 billion in 2003 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="65">Tax and customs authorities have selected VAT 187,0 billion in 2003. Sk and returned excessive VAT deductions amounted to a total of 103,2 billion. Sk.</seg>
<seg id="66">Consumer taxes</seg>
<seg id="67">The selection of excise duties (hereinafter referred to as the “SpD”) carried out the relevant financial or tax authorities and imported products subject to SpD customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="68">The share of SpD on tax revenues in the Czech Republic amounted to approximately 16% in 2003 and about 19% in Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="69">The total collection of SpD selected in the Czech Republic by financial and customs authorities in 2003 amounted to 85.6 billion. CZK and in Slovakia amounted to 38.0 billion. Sk.</seg>
<seg id="70">4. Progress of the audit action</seg>
<seg id="71">Cooperation between the SAO and the SAO SR took place in two stages.</seg>
<seg id="72">In the first phase, the comparison of imports and exports of selected commodities from customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia was carried out, in the second stage the results of this comparison were used in mutual verification of the implementation of selected commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and Slovakia and during inspections carried out in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="73">4.1.</seg>
<seg id="74">Preparation of the control action</seg>
<seg id="75">The first proposal for cooperation in parallel VAT inspections and SpD was presented at the working meeting of representatives of the SAO and the SAO SR in April 2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">In November 2003 a coordination meeting was carried out, which was agreed by the selection of commodities - types of goods, which represented a significant risk in compliance with customs and tax regulations: - hatch and spirits, customs tariff items no. 2207 and 2208, - tobacco and tobacco products, customs tariff items No.2401, 2402 and 2403, - computers and computer components, items and subpoles of customs tariff no. 8471 and 8473 30, - mobile phones and their accessories, lower-component conditions No 8525 20 91, 8525 20 99, 8529 90 40.</seg>
<seg id="77">Both parties agreed that the selection of tax entities to control will be carried out: a) from unguided items identified by the comparison of exports and imports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and Slovakia, b) from entities implementing imports and exports regularly or one-off in large volume, c) based on the findings from the audits carried out by selected financial and tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="78">4.2. Comparison of customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="79">In the first phase, a mechanism of mutual assignment of JCD items registered in customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia was tested on the sample of imports and exports of selected commodities for the month of October 2002.</seg>
<seg id="80">Subsequently, part of exports from the Czech Republic was compared to imports to Slovakia in 2002 and vice versa for selected commodities according to the customs tariff:</seg>
<seg id="81">- 2207 Ethylalcohol non-attered with volume alcohol content 80% Order. or more; ethyl alcohol and other distillates denatured, with any alcohol content,</seg>
<seg id="82">- 2208 Ethylalcohol non-attered with volume alcohol content less than 80% Order.; Distillates, liqueurs and other liquids,</seg>
<seg id="83">- 2401 Unprocessed tobacco; tobacco waste,</seg>
<seg id="84">- 2402 cigars (also with cut end), cigars (cigarillos) and tobacco cigarettes or tobacco substitutes,</seg>
<seg id="85">- 2403 Other tobacco products and tobacco substitutes; homogenized or reconstituted tobacco; tobacco extracts and punishment (esence),</seg>
<seg id="86">- 8525 20 91 Transmitting apparatus containing receiving device: For cellular network (mobile phones),</seg>
<seg id="87">- 8525 20 99 Transmitting apparatus containing receiving device: Other,</seg>
<seg id="88">- 8529 90 40 Parts and components suitable for use exclusively or mainly with number 8525 to 8528.</seg>
<seg id="89">Others: Parts and parts of the devices belonging to the sub pencil 8525 10 50, 8525 20 91, 8525 20 99, 8525 40 11 and 8527 90 92.</seg>
<seg id="90">Items JCD from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia were assigned to each other on the basis of conformity of individual paragraphs JCD (e.g. invoiced price, quantity, weight, registration mark of the vehicle transporting the cargo, date of transition of the state border, item of customs tariff, etc.).</seg>
<seg id="91">The results of the comparison are given in the following tables and graphs.</seg>
<seg id="92">Mutual assignment of individual imports and exports made it difficult among others the fact that business transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides.</seg>
<seg id="93">For example, exports from the Czech Republic declared on one export JCD were declared on multiple import JCDs in Slovakia, or the export JCD had a different number of items from import JCD.</seg>
<seg id="94">Other factors that affect the success of assignment was a different composition of data in customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia, as well as a time shift between the records of exports in the customs database of one country and records corresponding to imports in the customs database of the second country.</seg>
<seg id="95">The results of the comparison were used in the selection of control samples on audited financial or tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="96">Some tax entities, which have carried out imports, or exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia, which have failed to identify in both databases.</seg>
<seg id="97">In addition, some tax entities are selected for VAT verification in tax returns reported in tax returns, where the data on imports or exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia were found in both databases.</seg>
<seg id="98">4.3. Pilot control on the border customs crossing Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma</seg>
<seg id="99">The boundary customs transition for the performance of pilot control was selected on the basis of a joint analysis of unaccounted items JCD in customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="100">Based on the bilateral agreement between the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and Slovakia, it was introduced on border customs transitions between the Czech Republic and Slovakia to use control sheets.</seg>
<seg id="101">The aim of this measure was to eliminate customs and tax evasion as much as possible, to ensure an overview of the movement of means of transport transporting goods of commercial nature in the customs space and to create conditions for mutual comparison of customs records.</seg>
<seg id="102">The common pilot control was carried out from 8. 3. 2004 to 26. 3. 2004 and was focused on verifying this system of customs control.</seg>
<seg id="103">Procedure for use of control sheets on the border crossing Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma:</seg>
<seg id="104">1) Consideration of the vehicle, issuing the control sheet and its handover of the driver.</seg>
<seg id="105">2) Establishment of the vehicle in the marked sector in the parking lot.</seg>
<seg id="106">Customs discussion in the check-in hall of check-in Police of the Czech Republic, Police of the SR, Customs administration of the Czech Republic, Customs administration of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="107">The execution of the check-in confirmed the individual components by imprinting the stamp into the control sheet.</seg>
<seg id="108">3) Accessing the vehicle into the space of the implementation of physical control.</seg>
<seg id="109">Submission of the control sheet, JCD, or other documents of the customs administration worker - checking the execution of all prescribed tasks and documents.</seg>
<seg id="110">Practice of physical control by relevant components.</seg>
<seg id="111">Launch the vehicle from the customs area.</seg>
<seg id="112">Rise: When importing goods to the Czech Republic, weighing the vehicle directly carried out the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="113">When importing goods to Slovakia, we were carrying the workers authorized by a legal entity.</seg>
<seg id="114">Vehicles were registered in computer records after consideration.</seg>
<seg id="115">4.3.1 Control sample</seg>
<seg id="116">Export from the Czech Republic to Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="117">The control sample was selected on the basis of an analysis of records from the customs database of export of the Czech Republic in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="118">The composition of the control sample for exports is specified in Table 4.</seg>
<seg id="119">4.3.2. Control sheets and their records Export from the Czech Republic to Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="120">When exporting from the Czech Republic to Slovakia, the audits issued and registered the Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="121">The Customs Administration of the Czech Republic recorded registration numbers of these control sheets in the electronic database of export.</seg>
<seg id="122">From the number of 453 items JCD supervision of the SAO SR 256 cases of imports to Slovakia according to data from the customs database of the Czech Republic and Slovakia. The remaining 197 items of JCD identified the SAO SR in cooperation with the staff of the border crossing Drietoma.</seg>
<seg id="123">Export from Slovakia to the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="124">When exporting from Slovakia to the Czech Republic, control sheets issued and registered Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="125">From the total number of 339 items of JCD selected control sample of the SAO in cooperation with the staff of the border customs crossing Starý Hrozenkov assigned to 295 items JCD corresponding to the registration number of control sheets.</seg>
<seg id="126">The remaining 44 cases identified the workers of the border crossing Drietoma and the export of goods from Slovakia to the Czech Republic confirmed in their records.</seg>
<seg id="127">The SAO and the SAO of Slovakia did not find out shortcomings in the registration of selected cases of imports and exports of goods in 2002 at the border customs crossing Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma.</seg>
<seg id="128">4.4. Selected control findings when verifying business transactions</seg>
<seg id="129">Within the framework of international cooperation, the implementation of imports and exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia from the documents of customs administrations and financial, or tax authorities in the second country was verified.</seg>
<seg id="130">For selected tax entities, it was verified:</seg>
<seg id="131">- whether submitted by JCD were registered in customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia,</seg>
<seg id="132">- fulfilment of legal conditions for the application of VAT deduction when importing, refund of excessive VAT deduction and application of exemption from VAT in export.</seg>
<seg id="133">The verification of trade transactions was found:</seg>
<seg id="134">1. The SAO of SR asked for verification of the export of alcohol export in the statistical value of 56 989 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="135">The SAO identified the corresponding imports in the statistical value of 42 624 CZK in the customs database of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="136">2. The company engaged in importing and exporting photographic instruments and accessories applied in a VAT tax return for the month of December 2002 excessive VAT deduction of 3 740 664 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="137">In order to control the reported exports from the Czech Republic, the SAO chose 3 JCD (16 items) in the statistical value of 1 274 822 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="138">NKÚ SR identified 3 corresponding import JCD (17 items) in statistical value 1 724 321 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="139">VAT was paid to the relevant customs office in Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="140">3. The company, whose subject of business was mainly trade with optical instruments, was applied in 2002 by the total excessive VAT deduction by 4 1,36,000 CZK higher than the tax obligation.</seg>
<seg id="141">The SAO chose export JCD (32 items) in the statistical value of 7 154 124 CZK for the verification of the reported business activity.</seg>
<seg id="142">NKÚ SR found that this JCD corresponds to import JCD (12 items) with statistical value 9 653 827 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="143">VAT was paid to the relevant customs office in Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="144">4. Among other things, the company will buy goods for resale and sale, did not show VAT in the filed tax returns in 2002 and 2003 no export of goods.</seg>
<seg id="145">According to the customs database of the Czech Republic, the statistical value of the export of goods in 2002 was a total of 3 439 888 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="146">Based on these facts, the SAO selected 5 export JCD (5 items) in the total statistical value of 669 839 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="147">NKÚ SR identified 5 corresponding import JCD (5 items) in statistical value 1 012 656 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="148">The SAO's audit on the relevant tax office demonstrated the implementation of declared imports and VAT payment.</seg>
<seg id="149">5. The company, whose subject of business was, among other things, the purchase of goods for resale and sale, production, installation and repair of electrical machinery and apparatus, reported in 2002 in tax returns for VAT exports of goods worth 12 966 706 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="150">According to the customs database of the Czech Republic, the total export value was 14 474 381 CZK in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="151">The SAO submitted 17 export JCD (59 items) in the total statistical value of 2,975 122 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="152">NKÚ SR identified in the customs database of SR 13 JCD (50 items) in statistical value 3 621 370 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="153">In the customs database of the SR failed to identify the corresponding import JCD to 4 export JCD (9 items) in the total statistical value of 399 776 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="154">The competent tax office in Slovakia verified these imports at the tax entity.</seg>
<seg id="155">The tax entity, listed on JCD as importer to Slovakia, expressed in the letter from the local investigation that imports declared on Czech export JCD did not realize.</seg>
<seg id="156">The SAO therefore asked the local tax office to carry out the tax inspection of VAT and corporate income tax for the tax period 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="157">6. According to the customs database of the Czech Republic in 2002 tobacco stickers in the statistical value of 7 338 199 CZK and in 2003 in the statistical value of 12 228 545 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="158">In the tax returns, the company showed no exports in 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="159">The SAO chose 5 export JCD (5 items) in the total statistical value of 2 471 598 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="160">4 export JCD (4 items) in total statistical value 2 246 860 CZK NKÚ SR identified in the customs database of SR 7 JCD (7 items) in statistical value 2 919 514 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="161">The export JCD (1 item) in the statistical value of 224 738 CZK was not assigned to the corresponding import in the SR customs database.</seg>
<seg id="162">7. The company engaged in the provision of software did not show in tax returns for VAT for 2002 and 2003 exports of goods.</seg>
<seg id="163">According to the customs database of the Czech Republic, the statistical value of the export of goods in 2002 and 2003 was a total of 1 630 198 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="164">The SAO chose to verify in Slovakia 9 JCD (9 items) in the total statistical value of 755 588 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="165">8 JCD (8 items) identified 8 JCD (8 items) in the statistical value of 915 601 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="166">For export JCD (1 item) the statistical value of 68 286 CZK was not assigned to the corresponding import in the SR customs database.</seg>
<seg id="167">In these cases, it failed to identify in the customs database of the SR corresponding to imports to 6 JCD in the statistical value of 692 800 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="168">From this:</seg>
<seg id="169">- for 2 export JCD from the customs database of the Czech Republic in statistical value 293 024 CZK, the corresponding import JCD (see points 6 and 7) failed to identify in the customs database of the SR.</seg>
<seg id="170">Due to a certain error in entering data into the customs database, some registered imports could not be identified, e.g. in cases where the importer's name was missing or the error in the tax identification number (hereinafter referred to as the “VATČ").</seg>
<seg id="171">Therefore, it is not possible to state with certainty that the above-mentioned exports did not realize.</seg>
<seg id="172">- to 4 export JCD from the customs database of the Czech Republic were not demonstrated imports corresponding to exports from the Czech Republic to Slovakia in statistical value 399 776 CZK (see point 5).</seg>
<seg id="173">In these cases, there is a reasonable suspicion of fictitious export of goods for unauthorized application of VAT deduction.</seg>
<seg id="174">5. Checking imports and exports of goods and services within the framework of control of selected financial or tax authorities</seg>
<seg id="175">5.1. Control sample</seg>
<seg id="176">In order to verify the fulfilment of the obligations of tax entities in imports and exports of goods and services and evaluation of the level of cooperation between financial and customs authorities, writings of tax entities under the following criteria were selected for audited financial or tax authorities:</seg>
<seg id="177">1. from customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia, tax entities were selected: a) with the highest volume of imports, b) with the highest amount of VAT excluded, c) with the highest volume of exports,</seg>
<seg id="178">2. from the financial or tax authorities' records were selected tax entities according to the above: a) applied VAT deductions when importing, b) applied excessive VAT deductions, c) to return SpD, d) applied exemption from VAT in exports,</seg>
<seg id="179">3. tax entities where tax checks were carried out.</seg>
<seg id="180">The sample selection was carried out regardless of the country of destination with a focus on risk commodities.</seg>
