<p>
<seg id="1">Joint report on parallel inspections of expenditure on the construction of the Prague – Dresden motorway</seg>
<seg id="2">Úvodní slovo</seg>
<seg id="3">Without the existence of trans-European transport networks, it would be difficult to represent modern, dynamic and especially united Europe.</seg>
<seg id="4">Quality transport networks are an essential condition for maintaining and increasing the standard of living of Europeans.</seg>
<seg id="5">Creating conditions for fast, safe, reliable and cheap transport of persons and costs is an important task for state administration.</seg>
<seg id="6">It is the task of very demanding both organizational and technical and financial terms.</seg>
<seg id="7">European efforts to sustainable mobility often and difficult to seek compromises with interest in Europe to maintain a healthy and suitable environment for a person.</seg>
<seg id="8">The construction of transport infrastructure, even thanks to the necessary measures for the benefit of the environment, are financially demanding.</seg>
<seg id="9">Considered procedures and decision-making of state administration in the preparation and acquisition of transport constructions can bring significant savings in public financial resources, which can be used differently for the benefit of citizens.</seg>
<seg id="10">One of the tasks of audit institutions is to actively search for deficiencies that led to lower than achievable economy, efficiency and efficiency of expenditure on transport infrastructure construction.</seg>
<seg id="11">The auditing institutions should not only draw attention to the identified deficiencies, but recommend measures that will lead to an improvement in the condition for the benefit of citizens, for the benefit of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="12">Short summary</seg>
<seg id="13">Two Supreme Audit Institutions of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic) Bundesrechnungshof (hereinafter referred to as the “BRH”) and the Supreme Audit Office (hereinafter referred to as the “NKÚ”) carried out parallel control of expenditure on the construction of the Prague – Dresden motorway (D 8 motorway in the Czech Republic and the A 17 motorway in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="14">The highway is connected by a border bridge, which co-financed both countries.</seg>
<seg id="15">Thanks to cooperation with the SAO, BRH could perform a thorough control of the efficiency of the funds spent on the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="16">Based on close cooperation with BRH, the SAO acquired the necessary data on the amount of German costs on bridges and tunnels for comparative purposes.</seg>
<seg id="17">The Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany concluded a contract on the construction of the border bridge in 2000.</seg>
<seg id="18">According to the construction procedure, the completion date was finally scheduled for the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">During the procurement, however, the Road and Motorway Directorate of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the “ŘSD”) committed errors that led to the extension of the competition time and shortening the construction time.</seg>
<seg id="20">The contract was thus signed later than it was expected.</seg>
<seg id="21">The contractor agreed that the bridge will be built in a shorter time and ensures its completion in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="22">As a result, however, ŘSD had to accept a significant increase in the price of the bridge.</seg>
<seg id="23">As part of the joint inspection works, the prices of bridges on motorways D 8 and A 17, based on the conversion to m2 of the bridge structure area were compared.</seg>
<seg id="24">Statistical price analysis enabled to identify bridges with high costs of m2 of space.</seg>
<seg id="25">The analysis revealed that the border bridge was the most expensive bridge in the group of large bridges with a length of over 100 meters.</seg>
<seg id="26">The increase in the price could also be attributed to the delay that occurred during the custom procedure.</seg>
<seg id="27">When analyzing the costs of the construction of tunnels, auditors found that the prices of tunnels on the D 8 motorway are significantly higher than the prices of comparable tunnels in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="28">BRH and NKÚ now have a database of bridges and tunnels prices, which will be able to rely on future inspections of the efficiency of means used for transport infrastructure purposes.</seg>
<seg id="29">The construction of bridges of both control institutions recommends: standardization of bridges and the use of coupled steel-concrete and special structures only in cases where reinforced reinforced concrete bridges are not adequate.</seg>
<seg id="30">Her team spirit and informality belonged to the main emblems of cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the parallel control, auditors participated in their specific knowledge and skills.</seg>
<seg id="32">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="33">This report informs about the course and results of parallel inspections of funds spent on the construction of the motorway connecting Dresden and Prague (D 8 in the Czech Republic and A 17 in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="34">The audits were focused on economics, efficiency and efficiency of expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="35">The parallel control was carried out by BRH in Germany and the SAO in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="36">Parallel controls took place in 2005 and 2006.</seg>
<seg id="37">The SAO audited the economy, efficiency and efficiency of the expenditure of approximately CZK 20 billion, including VAT (approximately 690 million €) on the border section of the D 8, which has number 0807.</seg>
<seg id="38">64 million € from European funds (ISPA) should be used from this amount as planned.</seg>
<seg id="39">In addition to parallel control carried out together with the SAO, BRH audited the preparation and construction of the A 17 motorway in 2003 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="40">The funds spent on the construction of all three sections of the A 17 motorway amounted to approximately €670 million, and there will be 277 million € co-financed from European funds (EFRE).</seg>
<seg id="41">The highway from Prague to Dresden is part of the Trans-European Transport Corridor IV. Dresden – Central and southern part of Eastern Europe – Istanbul.</seg>
<seg id="42">The D 8 motorway leads from Prague through Ústí nad Labem to the state border.</seg>
<seg id="43">The A 17 motorway leads from the state border of the Czech Republic/SRN to Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="44">At the time of control, the border sections of both motorways were under construction.</seg>
<seg id="45">These sections were put into operation on 21 December 2006.</seg>
<seg id="46">On the German side is so highway completed until Dresden, while on the Czech side of the D 8 motorway is not completed, because section 0805 in the length of 16.4 km through the Czech Central Mountains between Řehlovice and Lovosice is still in the preparatory phase.</seg>
<seg id="47">According to the plan, the section 0805 between Prague and Ústí nad Labem has a protected landscape area of the Czech Central Mountains.</seg>
<seg id="48">According to the forecast carried out in the Czech Republic in 2001, the D 8 intensity of operation 22 940 vehicles per day should be in 2008 on the border section No 0807 of the D 8 motorway.</seg>
<seg id="49">According to the German forecast, the intensity of operation on the Czech border will be in 2010 about 25,000 vehicles per day.</seg>
<seg id="50">Germany and the Czech Republic concluded the Treaty between the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic on the interconnection of the German motorway A 17 and the Czech motorway D 8 on the joint state border by construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="51">Both countries participate in the construction of the bridge, so the inspection of the construction of this bridge was an important aspect of parallel inspections carried out by both control institutions.</seg>
<seg id="52">Cooperation BRH and NKÚ</seg>
<seg id="53">Since mid-2006, both the highest audit institutions have acted close cooperation in the control of the construction of the motorway connecting Prague and Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="54">Both sides had serious reasons for such cooperation:</seg>
<seg id="55">1.</seg>
<seg id="56">Germany is financially involved in the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="57">Its planning and construction consists in ŘSD.</seg>
<seg id="58">Therefore, BRH itself did not have the opportunity to check this construction project.</seg>
<seg id="59">2.</seg>
<seg id="60">The SAO did not have a comparative database needed to assess whether funds were used economically if it concerns the total level of bridges and tunnels on D 8.</seg>
<seg id="61">3.</seg>
<seg id="62">The SAO needed to assure the efficiency of expenditure taking into account the main technical parameters of the highway, especially the arrangement of bridges and tunnels, which should allow the same driving quality on both sides of the border.</seg>
