<seg id="2">Common Report on Parallel Control carried out by the Czech Supreme Audit Office (SAO) and the German Federal Court of Auditors (BRH)</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and overview</seg>
<seg id="4">Public procurement for goods and services of public contractors is very important both for state and private sphere.</seg>
<seg id="5">The role of the state is to use public resources as efficiently and economically and to ensure correct and regulated free competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU) the public procurement is a key factor for the success of a single economic space.</seg>
<seg id="7">In its regulations, the EU set limits in which the public contract must meet certain requirements to guarantee a wide and unlimited competitive environment throughout the EU.</seg>
<seg id="8">EU Member States must therefore transpose European procurement law into their national legislation and put it into practice.</seg>
<seg id="9">The Czech Republic and Germany have already done.</seg>
<seg id="10">For public procurement, which are values below the EU limits, the regulation of their entry into the competence of individual countries remains.</seg>
<seg id="11">In addition, public procurement is susceptible to corruption with subsequent high damage potential.</seg>
<seg id="12">Therefore, the contractors are obliged to accept reasonable measures in their procurement procedures for preventing corruption and incorrect favors (prevention of corruption).</seg>
<seg id="13">In January 2011, the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (Czech SAI – NKÚ) and the Federal Court of Auditors of Germany (German SAI – BRH) agreed to carry out parallel inspections in the field of procurement proceedings and prevention of corruption for land and transport constructions.</seg>
<seg id="14">Cooperation was also focused on the area of European procurement law as transposed into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="15">The audits also included procurement under European limits in order to affect corruption prevention area.</seg>
<seg id="16">The auditing findings of both supreme audit institutions are summarized in a joint report, which is among other things intended for international organisations such as the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).</seg>
<seg id="17">Areas of control and controlled institution</seg>
<seg id="18">The evaluation of BRH is based on the platforms of the above mentioned areas, which were carried out in German construction administrations responsible for federal transport and ground structures from 2011 to 2012.</seg>
