<seg id="32">In the Czech Republic, public procurement is governed by the Public Procurement Act and other legal regulations relating to orders with a value of above and under European limits.</seg>
<seg id="33">The procurement right has undergone substantial changes in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="34">The new rules strengthened the transparency of procurement procedures, opened space for greater competition and limited opportunities for corruption during the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="35">Basic aspects of procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="36">Regarding European procurement procedures, it is necessary to apply especially open and narrower management in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="37">In Germany, contracts under the European limit are awarded in accordance with national regulations (public call for participation in the competition, limited call for participation, meeting proceedings), but these are practically identical to the above conditions for European procurement proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="38">Public procurement in Germany is characterized by the principle of preference of open proceedings (where interested in a European scale) and public calls to participate (only in the case of national proceedings).</seg>
<seg id="39">In open proceedings and when prompting to participate in the competition, the offer may be submitted by any interested parties.</seg>
<seg id="40">Another important feature of the German procurement law is the support of small and medium-sized companies.</seg>
<seg id="41">This is achieved mainly by dividing the total public contract into a business specific parts and division into partial orders.</seg>
<seg id="42">By entering orders divided into these parts, the chances of participating in the management of the greatest amount of applicants are given.</seg>
