<seg id="115">Summary of the main principles of European procurement law and corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="116">European procurement law</seg>
<seg id="117">The European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted a directive on coordination of procedures for public procurement for public work, deliveries and services in order to ensure free movement of goods and services and directive on coordination of legal and administrative regulations relating to the review procedure in public procurement for deliveries and public procurement for construction work (directional proceedings), and these two directives should be transposed into national law.</seg>
<seg id="118">General procurement principles of the EU include in particular: a requirement for a competitive environment; a requirement for equal treatment or prohibition of discrimination; a request for transparency.</seg>
<seg id="119">In addition, the EU's procurement principles include the Coordination of Procedures in Public Procurement in addition, including provisions on construction projects whose total estimated value reaches or exceeds €5 million.</seg>
<seg id="120">These provisions affect: the content of procurement documents; the type of procurement procedure used; disclosure of certain information before, during and after the procedure; compliance with the deadline for acceptance of offers; qualification requirements that may be required after applicants; the selection criteria of the most suitable offer.</seg>
<seg id="121">Legal protection of applicants is governed by a directive on review proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="122">In case of a potential violation of the procurement law, applicants may have a review of the client's decision according to review procedures.</seg>
<seg id="123">Both countries have transposed EU requirements to national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="124">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="125">Meaning of corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="126">In any of both countries there is no legal definition, what actually corruption means.</seg>
<seg id="127">Generally, corruption is understood as abuse of personal (confidential) position for its own benefit.</seg>
<seg id="128">As a rule, this means that such abuse is incited by persons who will benefit from the benefit.</seg>
<seg id="129">Corruption can be an obstacle to competition and can cause serious economic losses.</seg>
<seg id="130">According to estimates, the total damage related to corruption is 5% of the world's economic performance.</seg>
<seg id="131">For EU, these costs are estimated at 1% of EU economic performance.</seg>
<seg id="132">If public procurement is involved in the order, the Convention restricting the competition or enabling dishonest negotiations can weaken trust in integrity, the ability and overall work of public administration.</seg>
<seg id="133">Therefore, the prevention of corruption is a fundamental task of the contractors.</seg>
<seg id="134">Practice and procedures must be checked especially in the areas of particularly susceptible to corruption in order to accept adequate measures to prevent it.</seg>
<seg id="135">Receiving preventive measures and implementing effective inspections can significantly reduce the susceptibility of the decision-making process to corruption.</seg>
<seg id="136">The procurement of orders for construction works is usually considered an area particularly susceptible to corruption.</seg>
<seg id="137">Measures in the field of corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="138">In Germany, corruption is prosecutable according to criminal and labour law, which is particularly related to active and passive bribery, receiving and offering significant benefits.</seg>
<seg id="139">The German Federal Government issued a manual with recommendations relating to the prevention of corruption in the federal administration and according to which they are applied throughout the procurement process outside the risk analysis of the following principles: the preference of open procurement; the principle of multiple control and transparent decision-making; the planning department, procurement and accounting phase; accurate and complete documentation of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="140">Moreover, further measures having preventive effect against corruption have become part of the procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="141">In 2011, the relevant federal Ministry of Information Technology supporting the system for monitoring orders for the construction of federal roads introduced.</seg>
<seg id="142">With this system, data can be as estimated costs, the total value of the order and involvement of private projection offices fully recorded and analyzed in order to determine the possible irregularities.</seg>
<seg id="143">In the Czech Republic, corruption is prosecuted according to criminal law, the level of labour or civil law is also considered.</seg>
<seg id="144">Legal requirement for transparency, equal treatment and prohibition of any discrimination throughout the procurement process (preparation and realization) is the most important part of corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="145">The anti-corruption measures in this area were established by the government in the “Government of the Government in the fight against corruption for the period 2011 to 2012”, which was updated for 2013 and 2014.</seg>
