<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the result of international cooperation in the audits of consumer tax management between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in 2006</seg>
<seg id="2">Úvodní slovo</seg>
<seg id="3">The submitted joint report informs about the course and result of international cooperation in parallel inspections implemented by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, focused on the management of excise duties in the period after the entry of both countries into the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="4">Cooperation was implemented on the basis of a contract on cooperation in control activities concluded in February 2006.</seg>
<seg id="5">The topic of parallel inspections was selected with regard to the fundamental change in the system of the selection of excise duty, which occurred in connection with the integration of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic into the internal market of the European Union from 1 May 2004.</seg>
<seg id="6">The functioning of the internal market of the European Union requires free movement of goods, including goods subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="7">The basic principle is to allow the circulation of goods unloaded taxes until the day of its delivery for final consumption.</seg>
<seg id="8">In accordance with the above-mentioned principle, the new legal regulation adopted in both countries, the movement of goods under the tax supervision in the condition of conditional exemption from tax.</seg>
<seg id="9">The system puts great demands on the tax administrator and assumes mutual compliance with the relevant administrative bodies of the Member States in the fight with tax fraud in this area.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the result of international cooperation in the audits of consumer tax management for the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005 1.</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Control number: (ČR) 05/34 (SR) 48/11</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of Control: (Czech Republic) Consumption Tax Administration (SR) Procedure of coloured authorities at the contract of beneficial taxes</seg>
<seg id="14">The Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the “NKÚ-ČR”) and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the “NSAO”) concluded on 8 February 2006 “The Treaty on Cooperation in Audit activities”.</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the contract was cooperation in parallel to the audits of the “ Consumption Tax Administration”, included in the Plan of Audit Plan of the SAO to 2005 under No. 05/34, and “Checking the procedure of the coloured authorities at the contract of beneficial taxes”, included into the 2006 Audit Plan of the SAO on 2006 under No. 48/11.</seg>
<seg id="16">Parallel control had the character of coordinated control.</seg>
<seg id="17">The cooperation consisted in exchange of information that the contracting parties could not obtain during the control of consumer tax administration in the territory of their country, and in the elaboration of the joint final report on the results of the audits within the meaning of European implementing directives for the implementation of the INTOSAI audit standards - Directive 31.</seg>
<seg id="18">On the territory of the Czech Republic control (hereinafter referred to as the “ČR”) carried out a group of controlling from the state budget department and from territorial trade unions of Central Bohemia, South Bohemia, Western Bohemia, northwest Bohemia, northeast Bohemia, southern Moravia, Central Moravia and North Moravia in the period from 7 February to 2 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">27 auditors were involved in the control.</seg>
<seg id="20">The audited bodies were the Directorate-General of Customs (hereinafter referred to as “GŘC”) and 11 financial offices.</seg>
<seg id="21">Within the GŘC, 12 selected customs authorities from the total number of 54.</seg>
<seg id="22">The audit on the territory of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the “SR”) carried out the financial and tax SAO section in cooperation with the SAO of SR Banská Bystrica and Košice on 5 customs offices from a total of 9 in the period from 13 February to 2 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="23">8 auditors were involved in the control.</seg>
<seg id="24">The aim of the parallel audits was to examine the procedure of customs authorities in the administration of excise duties and compliance with the relevant legislation applicable in both countries and the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="25">International cooperation was focused on the procedure of tax administrators in the performance of supervision of transport of goods subject to consumer tax, especially on the registration of initiated and terminated transport in the regime of conditional exemption from tax, and exchange of information within the mutual administrative assistance between consumer tax administrators of the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="26">2. Consumption tax management</seg>
<seg id="27">The management of excise duties in the Czech Republic carried out the financial authorities until 31 December 2003.</seg>
<seg id="28">From 1 January 2004 they took over this agenda customs authorities, which have so far chosen consumer tax only when imported.</seg>
<seg id="29">Consumer taxes are subject to mineral oils, alcohol, beer, wine and intermediates and tobacco products in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="30">The income of the state budget from excise duty in the Czech Republic amounted to CZK 82,8 billion in 2004. CZK and in revenues of the state budget of taxes and fees of CZK 424.7 billion. CZK with excise duty accounted for 19.5%.</seg>
<seg id="31">In 2005 the state budget intake amounted to 103,6 billion. CZK and share of revenues of the state budget from taxes and fees of CZK 460.4 billion. CZK was 22.5%.</seg>
<seg id="32">In 2004, the income from the excise duty on mineral oil in the state budget amounted to 80% of total income from this tax and in 2005 amounted to 90.9%.</seg>
