<p>
<seg id="1">Value Added Tax Administration in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Report on the results of subsequent control</seg>
<seg id="3">Úvodní slovo</seg>
<seg id="4">Taxes generally represent a key source of public income.</seg>
<seg id="5">It is therefore obvious that the highest audit institutions (Supreme Audit Institutions, as well as the “SAI”) should focus their attention on this area.</seg>
<seg id="6">An example is the value added fraud (hereinafter referred to as the “VAT”).</seg>
<seg id="7">In their case, a loss in the amount of EUR 100 billion is estimated annually in the European Union (hereinafter referred to as the “EU”).</seg>
<seg id="8">Already in 2005 the participants of the EUROSAI Congress in Bonn agreed on the need for very close cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="9">Within this cooperation, SAI can exchange control procedures, find the best solutions, etc.</seg>
<seg id="10">VAT is a very suitable area for control cooperation, as it is the only tax harmonized within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="11">The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the “NKÚ”) and the Federal Court of Auditors (Bundesrechnungshof, as well as the “BRH”) carried out the first parallel control event in the area of VAT in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="12">The relevant report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">Since fraudulent conduct concerning VAT does not restrict to a single country, but it is extended throughout the EU, close cooperation between the SAI is necessary to ensure a comprehensive evaluation of the steps taken to address this problem.</seg>
<seg id="14">Both SAI decided to further develop cooperation in this area and carried out subsequent parallel control.</seg>
<seg id="15">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="16">Control number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Subject control: (CZ) Value Added Tax Administration (D) Bilateral Audit with SAO (following check)</seg>
<seg id="18">Goal of control:</seg>
<seg id="19">(CZ) The aim of the auditing operation was to examine the procedure of financial authorities in the administration of VAT, in particular to verify the procedure in solving selected cases of commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as “Germany”), and to examine the procedures of tax administrators of both countries within international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) The auditing operation was proposed to evaluate the measures taken by tax administration to implement the recommendations issued by the SAO and BRH.</seg>
<seg id="21">The intention was also to cover other areas related to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="22">The resulting control finding was intended for comparison with the proven practice (if any).</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited period was 2006 to 2008, in the case of factual contexts and the period of the previous and the following, until the end of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="24">2. Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control events</seg>
<seg id="25">Subsequent control of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two SAI.</seg>
<seg id="26">During previous parallel controls, suspicious cases of intra-Community transactions were revealed.</seg>
<seg id="27">Some of them have requested another verification.</seg>
<seg id="28">On the basis of control findings, both SAI recommendations were formulated on VAT administration.</seg>
<seg id="29">The subsequent control action served to evaluate the measures taken in response to this recommendation and to verify selected suspicious cases.</seg>
<seg id="30">The auditing operation also focused on selected cases of high-risk intra-Community transactions, mutual assistance in debt recovery and inspections of VAT inspections for large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="31">During control of VAT administration in selected areas in both countries, auditors came to the following control findings:</seg>
<seg id="32">1. Recommendation from previous control</seg>
<seg id="33">• Recommendation 1: Conditions of registration of payers should be harmonised within the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">Differences were found in previous parallel inspections by comparing VAT registration systems in both countries.</seg>
